Here's the complete consolidated checklist. Admin PowerShell or cmd required for all of this.

**Phase 1 — Baseline the problem (optional but recommended)**

Start a DNS Client ETW trace so you have a before/after comparison.

```powershell
# Logman version
logman create trace "DnsTrace" -ow -o C:\temp\dns.etl `
  -p "Microsoft-Windows-DNS-Client" 0xFFFFFFFF 0xFF `
  -nb 16 16 -bs 1024 -f bincirc -max 100 -ets

# OR PowerShell native version
New-EtwTraceSession -Name "DnsTrace" -LocalFilePath "C:\temp\dns.etl" `
  -MaximumFileSize 100 -LogFileMode 0x00000002
Add-EtwTraceProvider -SessionName "DnsTrace" `
  -Guid "{1C95126E-7EEA-49A9-A3FE-A378B03DDB4D}" `
  -Level 0xFF -MatchAnyKeyword 0xFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFF
```

Let it run 5-10 minutes, then stop:

```powershell
logman stop "DnsTrace" -ets
# OR
Remove-EtwTraceSession -Name "DnsTrace"
```

Read it:

```powershell
Get-WinEvent -Path "C:\temp\dns.etl" -Oldest |
  Where-Object { $_.Id -eq 3006 } |
  Select-Object TimeCreated, ProcessId, @{n='Query';e={$_.Properties[0].Value}} |
  Group-Object ProcessId, Query | Sort-Object Count -Descending
```

**Phase 2 — Disable LLMNR (port 5355)**

Registry (PowerShell):
```powershell
New-Item -Path "HKLM:\SOFTWARE\Policies\Microsoft\Windows NT\DNSClient" -Force | Out-Null
Set-ItemProperty -Path "HKLM:\SOFTWARE\Policies\Microsoft\Windows NT\DNSClient" -Name "EnableMulticast" -Value 0 -Type DWord
```

GPO path: `Computer Configuration → Administrative Templates → Network → DNS Client → Turn off multicast name resolution → Enabled`

**Phase 3 — Disable mDNS (port 5353)**

Registry (PowerShell):
```powershell
Set-ItemProperty -Path "HKLM:\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Services\Dnscache\Parameters" -Name "EnableMDNS" -Value 0 -Type DWord
```

No GPO template for this one by default — registry only. Reboot required.

**Phase 4 — Disable WPAD**

Check first whether anything needs it:
```powershell
netsh winhttp show proxy
Get-ItemProperty "HKCU:\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Internet Settings" | Select-Object AutoConfigURL, AutoDetect, ProxyServer, ProxyEnable
```

If `AutoConfigURL` is empty and `AutoDetect` is 0, you're safe to disable. If either is set, skip this phase or confirm with whoever manages the proxy config.

Registry (PowerShell):
```powershell
New-Item -Path "HKLM:\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Internet Settings\Wpad" -Force | Out-Null
Set-ItemProperty -Path "HKLM:\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Internet Settings\Wpad" -Name "WpadOverride" -Value 1 -Type DWord
```

Also clear any WinHTTP-level proxy and turn off auto-detect for the current user:

```cmd
netsh winhttp reset proxy
```
```powershell
Set-ItemProperty "HKCU:\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Internet Settings" -Name "AutoDetect" -Value 0 -Type DWord
```

GPO path: `User Configuration → Administrative Templates → Windows Components → Internet Explorer → Disable changing Automatic Configuration settings` (indirect — the cleaner GPO method is to deploy a Proxy Settings policy with auto-detect explicitly off).

Service-level option (more aggressive, only if you never want WPAD at all):
```powershell
Stop-Service WinHttpAutoProxySvc -Force
Set-Service WinHttpAutoProxySvc -StartupType Disabled
```

**Phase 5 — Disable IPv6 transition technologies (Teredo, 6to4, ISATAP)**

PowerShell (preferred — surgical, leaves IP Helper service running):
```powershell
Set-NetTeredoConfiguration -Type Disabled
Set-Net6to4Configuration -State Disabled
Set-NetIsatapConfiguration -State Disabled
```

Registry equivalent:
```powershell
New-Item -Path "HKLM:\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Services\Tcpip6\Parameters" -Force | Out-Null
Set-ItemProperty -Path "HKLM:\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Services\Tcpip6\Parameters" -Name "DisabledComponents" -Value 0x01 -Type DWord
```

Note: `DisabledComponents` is a bitmask. `0x01` disables tunnel interfaces. `0xFF` disables all IPv6. Don't use `0xFF` unless you're sure nothing on your network needs IPv6.

GPO path: `Computer Configuration → Administrative Templates → Network → TCPIP Settings → IPv6 Transition Technologies` — separate policies for Teredo, 6to4, ISATAP, each set to Disabled State.

Service-level option (most aggressive, kills all of IP Helper):
```powershell
Stop-Service iphlpsvc -Force
Set-Service iphlpsvc -StartupType Disabled
```

Only do this if you don't need DirectAccess and don't use any software that depends on the IP Helper API.

**Phase 6 — Disable NetBIOS over TCP/IP (belt-and-suspenders)**

NetBIOS is another legacy fallback that generates broadcast traffic (UDP 137/138) and is exploitable by the same Responder-style attacks as LLMNR. Usually worth turning off at the same time.

Per-adapter via PowerShell:
```powershell
Get-WmiObject -Class Win32_NetworkAdapterConfiguration -Filter "IPEnabled=True" |
  ForEach-Object { $_.SetTcpipNetbios(2) }
```

The `2` means "Disable NetBIOS over TCP/IP." `0` is "default from DHCP," `1` is "enabled."

GPO path: no direct template — deploy via DHCP option 1 (Microsoft disable NetBIOS option) or a startup script running the above.

**Phase 7 — Reboot**

```powershell
Restart-Computer
```

Most of the DNS Client and TCP/IP changes don't fully take effect until a reboot.

**Phase 8 — Verify**

Re-run the trace from Phase 1. The 5353/5355 queries should be gone or drastically reduced. If anything's still showing up, the query name in the trace will tell you what's still asking.

Quick sanity checks:
```powershell
# Confirm mDNS is off
Get-ItemProperty "HKLM:\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Services\Dnscache\Parameters" -Name EnableMDNS

# Confirm LLMNR is off
Get-ItemProperty "HKLM:\SOFTWARE\Policies\Microsoft\Windows NT\DNSClient" -Name EnableMulticast

# Confirm IPv6 transition tech is off
Get-NetTeredoConfiguration
Get-Net6to4Configuration
Get-NetIsatapConfiguration

# Confirm NetBIOS is off per adapter
Get-WmiObject -Class Win32_NetworkAdapterConfiguration -Filter "IPEnabled=True" |
  Select-Object Description, TcpipNetbiosOptions
# TcpipNetbiosOptions should be 2

# Confirm WPAD
netsh winhttp show proxy
```

**Summary of what this accomplishes:**

- 5355 (LLMNR) → gone at source
- 5353 (mDNS) → gone at source
- 137/138 (NetBIOS) → gone at source
- `wpad` queries → gone at source
- `isatap.*` / `teredo.*` queries → gone at source
- `_ldap._tcp.dc._msdcs.*` → still happens if domain-joined (that's Netlogon, leave it)
- NCSI probes to `msftconnecttest.com` / `msftncsi.com` → still happen (don't kill these, they're how Windows determines if it has internet)

That's the complete source-side elimination. Nothing on this list involves firewall filtering — it's all turning off the actual generating subsystems.
